The 2018 (original) collection reverses what were quire 8 (fols. 44-51) and quire 9 (fols. 52-57)

msContents.summary: This manuscript, written by two scribes in 199 vellum leaves with illuminated initials and border ornament, contains complete versions of fifteen of the tales: Man of Law, Shipman, Prioress, Rime of Sir Thopas, Melibeus, Monk, Nun's Priest, Doctor, Pardoner, Wife of Bath, Friar, Summoner, Clerk, Second Nun and Canon's Yeoman. It lacks the Prologue, the tales of the Miller, Reeve, and Cook and contains incomplete tales of the Knight, Merchant, Squire, Parson, and Gamelyn. One of 57 major surviving 15th century manuscripts of the tales, it is textually related to the Petworth Ms. and Cambridge Ms. Mm 2.5 (Manly and Rickert's group D).

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, lower right recto

p.signatures: Eighteenth-century signatures put in when manuscript was rebound

p.catchwords: In brown ink and often framed

layoutDesc.layout: Single column of forty lines; frame-ruled in both light brown and rose-coloured ink; incipits and explicits in red ink; marginal headings in red ink, glosses in Man of Law's Tale and Pardoner's Tales, a few in the Parson's Tale; running title in red ink on verso and recto preceded by blue paraphs flourished with red or gold flourished with blue ink; written area: 210 x 110

decoDesc.decoNote: Five-line gold initials with champe sprays on coloured background used for beginnings of tales, three-line initials in same colours for links: Blue, pink, orange and green; paragraph marks are blue alternating with gold for stanzas in Man of Law, Prioress, Monk; also used for glosses and running titles

history.provenance: On fol. 80v, in the gutter, is the note "This Book | Cost 2d the doing."; Sold to Thorpe at the Richard Heber sale in 1836, who sold the MS to Sir Thomas Phillipps; The Phillipps library sold this and other MSS to A. S. W. Rosenbach in November 1923 (Morris 1988, p. 42)
